# Hash-set demo

## Overview

This little project is aimed to showcase a simple example of a hash set. It
provides a build and test lightweight framework which can be reused for other C
projects as well, enjoy!

## Introduction

While complicated data structures are abundant and often overlooked at in
popular developer tools (such as Java, Python, Rust), having them working in C
requires an explicit declaration. A simple example which is particularly useful
to delve into data structure is certainly the hash set.

While searching a term in an array has a $0(n)$ time complexity, hash sets in
most situation will provide time complexity close to $O(1)$, which makes them
ideal to store information, and can be easily extended into hash table,
providing the basic tool for caching.

What is presented here is a project showcasing a simple API for interaction with
a hash set, with a dedicated `Makefile` orchestrating the build and the unit
testing. The final result will be an executable taking the input arguments and
arranging them in a hash map.

## Storing and retrieving data

The idea behind a hash set is an array of size $N$. The elements of the hash set
will be stored depending on the hash $H$ of a given element, which decides the
array's address $i$ according to the formula

$$
i=\mod(H,N)
$$

$N$ is the **capacity** of given set.

This operation is not dependent on $N$, therefore is commonly agreed that this
algorithm is $O(1)$.

## Handling data collisions

As data collisions can occur (i.e. two object share the same array position), a
linked list structure for the given array position will provide a way to
navigate through the different candidates. To avoid this issue drifting the
algorithm towards a $O(n)$ complexity, the array in the hash set needs to be
resized accordingly.

The resizing can be decided when the ratio between the population of the set and
its capacity reaches a certain ration, this is called **load factor**, and it is
usually decided to have a value of 0.75 (as it happens in Java).

Because resizing a set consists in assigning a new hash to each element, it's
complexity will be $O(n)$ as well, to avoid time complexity issues it is done
exponentially, so the number of times it will be needed will be around
$\log(n)$.

## The presented case

While all the previous operations are performed under the hood within the high
level development frameworks, this project provides a way to have a closer look
at how the elements are stored inside the data structure, as the user has the
possibility to create a dataset populated by strings. The strings will be the
executable's arguments, and the following input

```bash
./hash-set-demo this was a very very fun job to do
```

will print on the screen the following output

```
You insert `very` at least twice
array[00]
array[01] -> `a`
array[02]
array[03]
array[04] -> `this`
array[05]
array[06] -> `very`
array[07] -> `was` -> `job`
array[08]
array[09]
array[10]
array[11]
array[12]
array[13] -> `fun`
array[14]
array[15] -> `do` -> `to`
```

As it can be seen, as collisions happen they are manageable, and usually not too
likely to compromise performance. The program also lets the user know when there
are duplicates, as a set data structure is designed to quickly detect such
instances.

A simple API is defined in `lib/hashset.h`, while the `src/` directory will
provide the implementations. The `check/` directory provides unit tests to be
turned into tests by means of the
[checkmk](https://manpages.ubuntu.com/manpages/resolute/man1/checkmk.1.html)
awk script, which turns those test case into C source code, which in turn is
compiled into test. The orchestration is managed by a custom `Makefile` with no
need for elaborate `automake` or `cmake` calls.

## Requirements

* The dev tools including a C compiler
* the `checkmk` library, is usually available in the `check` package, it can be
  installed typing the following

```bash
sudo apt install check
```

## Usage

To build the executable, simply type

```bash
make
```

This will run:

* The building of the linked `.o` files.
* The building of the test files.
* The execution of the tests.
* The execution of the main executable.

To run the executable, type

```bash
./hash-set-demo this was a very very fun job to do
```

## Conclusion

While this started as a personal holiday fun game, it was surely a way to delve
deeply into data structures and their compromises. I strongly believe that by
virtue of example, developers will do their job with greater awareness of their
work flow when such structures are closely looked at.

The final result was satisfactory to my taste:
it can be easily developed into a hash table, and it
can be used for future projects. Memory fallbacks were not easily tested, but I
put safe guards wherever memory allocation functions were employed.

In the future I would like to use this GitHub space to delve into more data
structures and building simple command line tools, like a command line
interpreter, to employ such structures.

As much as educational as this project can be, I would personally like to keep
this simplicity in future projects, given how little allowed me to develop a
full CI-CD model.
